qas.question: What are code points in the range U+D800-U+DBFF known as?
What are code points in the range U+DC00-U+DFFF known as?
what is another name for a high-surrogate code point?
what is another name for a low-surrogate code point?
What is known as a character's scalar value?

answers.text: the range of code points that are available for use as characters

qas.question: What is a low-surrogate followed by a high-surrogate called?
What is another name for a surrogate pair?
How many points are represented inside of BMP?
Which kinds of code points are valid by themselves?
What is the individual number of code points called?

context: Code points in the range U+D800–U+DBFF (1,024 code points) are known as <a0_0>high-surrogate code points<a0_0/>, and code points in the range U+DC00–U+DFFF (1,024 code points) are known as <a1_0>low-surrogate code points<a1_0/>. A high-surrogate code point (also known as a <a2_0>leading surrogate<a2_0/>) followed by a low-surrogate code point (also known as a <a3_0><b6_0>trailing surrogate<b6_0/><a3_0/>) together form <b5_0>a surrogate pair<b5_0/> used in UTF-16 to represent <b7_0>1,048,576<b7_0/> code points outside BMP. <b8_0>High and low<b8_0/> surrogate code points are not valid by themselves. Thus <a4_0>the range of code points that are available for use as characters<a4_0/> is U+0000–U+D7FF and U+E000–U+10FFFF (1,112,064 code points). The value of these code points (i.e., excluding surrogates) is sometimes referred to as the character's <b9_0>scalar value<b9_0/>.
